The paper deals with the problem of distributed fusion of multiobject posteriors in the context of tracking, which is a problem that is relevant to several sub-fields of computer science. However, the focus on labeled random finite sets filtering and the use of a generalized covariance intersection method suggest that the paper is most likely to be classified under the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category. The paper also involves computer vision (cs.CV) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI) techniques, as well as information theory (cs.IT) and machine learning (cs.LG) concepts, which are all relevant to the problem of tracking. However, the emphasis on distributed fusion and the use of a specific filtering framework suggest that these sub-categories are less likely to be the primary classification for the paper.
